## Conversation
User: "This integration feels like it may be blocking the user process.
Please confirm if that's true and if it is, ensure that it doesn't block...
you can upload in a background thread." Investigated empirically rather
than asserting; found the run path non-blocking but process EXIT held
hostage by the exporter's idle keep-alive socket.

## Actions
Experiment script (3 ADK invocations via InMemoryRunner + ScriptedLlm,
inline HTTP server as the agents endpoint) in four modes:
- baseline (no weave.init): agent loop 10ms, exit 23ms after done
- fast endpoint: loop 16ms, beforeExit fired +2ms, but EXIT +6017ms
- slow endpoint (3s/response): loop 17ms (!), exit +9012ms
- handle dump after flushOTel (9ms): one ref'd client Socket to the
  endpoint remained; loop could not drain until the SERVER closed it
  (node http server default keepAliveTimeout 5s → the ~6s constant).
Mechanism: beforeExit cannot fire while a ref'd handle exists, so even the
provider's shutdown hook waits on the socket. Fix: keepAlive:false on the
OTLP exporter in src/genai/provider.ts buildOtlpExporter.

## Errors & Mistakes
None; the 6s constant was initially mysterious until the active-handles
dump identified the keep-alive socket (the 9012ms slow case = 3s shutdown
flush + ~6s socket linger, corroborating).

## Dead Ends
- Unref'ing the socket instead of disabling keep-alive: node's http.Agent
  is supposed to unref free-pool sockets, but the exporter's socket stayed
  ref-holding in practice; no exporter config exposes socket refs, and
  reaching into transport internals is fragile. keepAlive:false is the
  robust, supported knob (flows into httpAgentOptions).

## Hints for Future Agents
- "Integration blocks the process" reports for Node SDKs: check EXIT
  behavior, not just run-path latency. process._getActiveHandles() after
  the workload + hasRef() identifies the holder.
- The run path was never blocking: span building is in-memory; OTLP export
  is async event-loop I/O (node's equivalent of a background thread); a
  3s/request endpoint did not slow the 17ms agent loop.
- This affects all agents-endpoint emitters (ADK, pi, openai-agents otel),
  which is why the fix sits below the ADK stack as its own PR.

## Codebase Discoveries
- BatchSpanProcessor unrefs its flush timer (core unrefTimer), and the
  weave client's call batcher only schedules timers when calls are queued —
  neither holds the loop; the socket was the sole culprit.

## Open Questions
- Hung-endpoint exit bound is the exporter's request timeout (default 10s);
  acceptable, not configurable via our settings today.
